.TH STING 1 "11 July 2026" "sting 1.0" "User Commands"
.SH NAME
sting \- hide an encrypted payload inside a PNG image, and recover it
.SH SYNOPSIS
.B sting
.B \-\-hide
.B \-c
.I CARRIER
[\fB\-i\fR \fISECRET\fR] [\fB\-o\fR \fISTEGO\fR] [\fIgisp options\fR]
.br
.B sting
.B \-\-extract
[\fB\-i\fR \fISTEGO\fR] [\fB\-o\fR \fISECRET\fR] [\fIgisp options\fR]
.br
.B sting
.B \-\-capacity
.B \-c
.I CARRIER
.SH DESCRIPTION
.B sting
layers a low-capacity, pseudo-random least-significant-bit (LSB)
steganographic channel on top of the
.BR gisp (1)
file-encryption utility.  A secret is first encrypted by gisp using
XChaCha20-Poly1305 authenticated encryption with an Argon2id-derived key, and
only the resulting opaque container is scattered across the carrier image.
.PP
Content confidentiality and integrity come entirely from gisp:
.B sting
treats the ciphertext as an opaque blob and never sees, derives, or stores the
passphrase.  This holds unconditionally.
.PP
.I Stealth
\(em concealing that a payload exists at all \(em is a weaker, conditional
property.  Without a stego-key
.B sting
runs in a
.B detectable
mode: the header sits at a fixed, public location and carries a constant
marker, so anyone with
.B sting
can confirm a payload is present (its contents stay encrypted).  Supply a
.B \-\-stego\-key
to place the header and payload by a secret-derived layout instead, leaving
nothing to recognise; a wrong stego-key then looks exactly like a clean image.
Even so, touching at most 3% of the usable colour samples and using LSB
.I matching
(\(+-1 embedding) rather than LSB replacement only
.I lowers
the statistical signal that steganalysis looks for; it does not make the
channel provably undetectable.  No scheme conceals a payload from an adversary
who also holds the original carrier, since a pixel-wise diff reveals every
changed sample; that comparison is outside
.BR sting 's
threat model.  The stego-key is an independent secret and is never the gisp
passphrase, nor is it forwarded to gisp.
.PP
A path of
.B \-
selects standard input or standard output, so
.B sting
composes into the same pipelines as gisp.
.SH OPTIONS
.SS Mode
.TP
\fB\-H\fR, \fB\-\-hide\fR
Encrypt \fISECRET\fR with gisp and embed the container into \fICARRIER\fR.
.TP
\fB\-X\fR, \fB\-\-extract\fR
Recover the container from \fISTEGO\fR and decrypt it with gisp.
.TP
\fB\-\-capacity\fR
Report how many payload bytes \fICARRIER\fR can hold, then exit.
.SS Files
.TP
\fB\-c\fR, \fB\-\-carrier\fR \fIFILE\fR
Cover PNG to embed into (hide and capacity modes).
.TP
\fB\-i\fR, \fB\-\-in\fR \fIFILE\fR
The secret to hide, or the stego PNG to read.  Default is \fB\-\fR.
.TP
\fB\-o\fR, \fB\-\-output\fR \fIFILE\fR
Where to write the result.  Default is \fB\-\fR.
.TP
\fB\-\-ratio\fR \fIFRACTION\fR
Ceiling on the fraction of samples that may be modified.  Must satisfy
0 < r <= 0.03; the default and maximum is 0.03 (3%).
.SS Stealth (sting's own secret, never forwarded to gisp)
.TP
\fB\-\-stego\-key\fR \fISTR\fR
Place the header and payload by a layout keyed with the secret \fISTR\fR, so
the embedding cannot be located or confirmed without it.  Both hiding and
extracting must use the same key.  This is separate from the gisp passphrase.
.TP
\fB\-\-stego\-key\-file\fR \fIFILE\fR
Read the stego-key from \fIFILE\fR (a single line; one trailing newline is
stripped).  Mutually exclusive with \fB\-\-stego\-key\fR.
.SS Passphrase (forwarded to gisp)
.TP
\fB\-\-passphrase\-fd\fR \fIN\fR
Have gisp read the passphrase from file descriptor \fIN\fR.
.TP
\fB\-\-passphrase\-file\fR \fIFILE\fR
Have gisp read the passphrase from \fIFILE\fR.
.PP
With neither option, gisp prompts on the controlling terminal (and, when
hiding, asks for confirmation).
.SS Key derivation (forwarded to gisp when hiding)
.TP
\fB\-p\fR, \fB\-\-opslimit\fR \fINUM\fR
Argon2id CPU operations limit.
.TP
\fB\-m\fR, \fB\-\-memlimit\fR \fIBYTES\fR
Argon2id memory limit in bytes.
.SS Resource ceilings (forwarded to gisp when extracting)
.TP
\fB\-\-max\-opslimit\fR \fINUM\fR
.TQ
\fB\-\-max\-memlimit\fR \fIBYTES\fR
.TQ
\fB\-\-max\-filesize\fR \fIBYTES\fR
.TQ
\fB\-\-min\-password\-length\fR \fIN\fR
.TQ
\fB\-\-allow\-weak\-password\fR
See
.BR gisp (1).
.SS Miscellaneous
.TP
\fB\-g\fR, \fB\-\-gisp\fR \fIPATH\fR
Path to the gisp executable.  Otherwise sting tries \fB$STING_GISP\fR, then
\fBgisp\fR on \fBPATH\fR, then \fB~/Scripts/gisp/src/gisp\fR.
.TP
\fB\-q\fR, \fB\-\-quiet\fR
Suppress non-error messages.
.TP
\fB\-h\fR, \fB\-\-help\fR
Display a usage message and exit.
.TP
\fB\-v\fR, \fB\-\-version\fR
Display version information and exit.
.SH "CARRIER IMAGES"
Carriers must be PNG images.  8-bit L, LA, RGB and RGBA images are used
directly; palette and 1-bit images are promoted to true colour first, so the
stego output is a normal true-colour PNG (and therefore larger than a palette
original).  16-bit images are refused.  Only colour channels are used, never
alpha, and samples of fully transparent pixels are skipped.
.SH "OUTPUT FILES"
A named output is written to a temporary file in the same directory and then
renamed into place, so a reader never observes a partial result.  The
permissions differ by role.  A secret recovered by \fB\-\-extract\fR is created
mode 0600, matching
.BR gisp (1),
so the plaintext is private from the moment it exists.  A stego image written
by \fB\-\-hide\fR instead takes the ordinary umask default, because a picture
that alone among its neighbours is readable only by its owner is precisely the
anomaly the rest of sting works to avoid; if the output already exists, its
current mode is preserved.  Writing to standard output, or to a target that is
not a regular file, changes no permissions at all.
.SH "EXIT STATUS"
.TP
.B 0
Success.
.TP
.B 1
Operational failure: a wrong password, a tampered or corrupt image, a carrier
too small for the payload, or an I/O error.  As in gisp, a wrong password and
tampered data are deliberately indistinguishable.
.TP
.B 2
Command-line usage error.
.SH EXAMPLES
Hide a file, prompting for a passphrase on the terminal:
.PP
.RS
.nf
sting \-\-hide \-c cover.png \-i secret.txt \-o innocent.png
.fi
.RE
.PP
Recover it again:
.PP
.RS
.nf
sting \-\-extract \-i innocent.png \-o secret.txt
.fi
.RE
.PP
Non-interactive pipeline, passphrase on descriptor 3:
.PP
.RS
.nf
tar c dir | sting \-H \-c cover.png \-i \- \-o \- \-\-passphrase\-fd 3 3<key > s.png
sting \-X \-i \- \-o \- \-\-passphrase\-fd 3 3<key < s.png | tar x
.fi
.RE
.SH ENVIRONMENT
.TP
.B STING_GISP
Path to the gisp executable, consulted after \fB\-\-gisp\fR and before
\fBPATH\fR.
